page.title: 01SEA BANK LANDSCAPE
page.content: THE SOUTH WEST SQUARE OF THIS BLOCK IS CROSSED FROM NW TO SE BY A SEA BANK WHICH WAS CONSTRUCTED AFTER YHE EAST COAST FLOODS OF JAN. 1953. THE MATERIAL FOR THE BANK WAS EXCAVATED FROM THE SEAWARD SIDE AND THE RESULTING LONG NARROW DEPRESSION HAS FILLED WITH WATER AND PART OF IT IS FRESH. THIS FORMS AN IMPORTANT FEATURE OF DONNA NOOK NATURE RESERVE. DEAWARDS OF THIS 'FLASH' IS A ZONE OF SAND DUNE THE EASTERN FOOT OF WHICH IS THE HIGH TIDE (SPRING TIDE) MARK>. THE BEACH IS PART OF THE RAF DONNA NOOK BOMBING RANGE. SEE ENTRY FOR BLOCK 05400396 FOR TEXT AND PHOTOGRAPHS.
